      "body": "Approach NACK \r\n\r\nI do not think this is the best future proof way to accomplish the goal. In C++ 23 `std::expected` is introduced, which is a better way (imo) to do for explicit error handling. E.g [link](https://towardsdev.com/cpp-23-std-expected-tutorial-modern-error-handling-guide-2026-9494ebb44e81) [link2](https://www.cppstories.com/2024/expected-cpp23/)\r\n\r\nYes we are currently on C++ 20 but a \"polyfill\" `std::expected` is already introduced in the code as [`util::Expected<T, E>`](https://github.com/bitcoin/bitcoin/blob/master/src/util/expected.h)\r\n\r\nThis makes the upgrade path to C++23 an easy search and replace and is a better way to do explicit error handling / remove the `ok` from the errors.",
